{"cursor":"53129","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n, Philippines]] s penetrate the sand surrounding a mangrove tree.]]\n\n\n'Mangroves' are various types of trees up to medium height and shrubs that grow\nin saline coastal sediment habitats in the tropics and subtropics â mainly\nbetween latitudes  N and  S. The remaining mangrove forest areas of\nthe world in 2000 was 53,190 square miles (137,760 kmÂ²) spanning 118\ncountries and territories. Giri, C. et al. Status and distribution of\nmangrove forests of the world using earth observation satellite data. Glob.\nEcol. Biogeogr. 20, 154-159 (2011). The word is used in at\nleast three senses: (1) most broadly to refer to the habitat and entire plant\nassemblage or 'mangal', Hogarth, Peter J. (1999) The Biology\nof Mangroves Oxford University Press, Oxford, England, ISBN 0-19-850222-2.\nfor which the terms 'mangrove forest [[biome]]', 'mangrove swamp' and 'mangrove\nforest' are also used, (2) to refer to all trees and large shrubs in the\nmangrove swamp, and (3) narrowly to refer to the mangrove family of plants, the\nRhizophoraceae, or even more specifically just to mangrove trees of the genus\n[[Rhizophora]]. The term \"\" comes to English from Spanish (perhaps by way of\nPortuguese), and is of Caribbean origin, likely TaÃ­no. It was earlier \"mangrow\"\n(from Portuguese {{lang|pt|mangue}} or Spanish {{lang|es|mangle}}), but this was\ncorrupted via folk etymology influence of \"grove\".\n\nThe mangrove biome, or mangal, is a distinct saline woodland or shrubland\nhabitat characterized by depositional coastal environments, where fine sediments\n(often with high organic content) collect in areas protected from high-energy\nwave action. Mangroves dominate three-quarters of tropical coastlines. The saline conditions tolerated by various mangrove species range\nfrom brackish water, through pure seawater (30 to 40 ppt), to water concentrated\nby evaporation to over twice the salinity of ocean seawater (up to 90 ppt).\n\nAn increase in mangroves has been suggested for climate change mitigation. [http://www.scientificamerican.com/article.cfm?id=restoring-\nmangroves-may-prove-cheap-way-to-cool-climate Restoring Mangroves May Prove\nCheap Way to Cool Climate] July 31, 2012 Scientific American [http://phys.org/news/2011-04-declining-mangroves-shield-\nglobal.html Declining mangroves shield against global warming] April 3, 2011\nPhys.Org\n","linknr":1116,"url":"Mangrove","recorded":1362372909,"links":121,"instances":["nature","biology","environmental","australia","pakistan","geology","ecology","biology"],"pdf":["http://www.dpi.inpe.br/referata/arq/2010_09_Marilia/Giri_etal_2010.pdf","http://www.dpi.inpe.br/referata/arq/2010_09_Marilia/Giri_etal_2010.pdf","http://www.glomis.com/ej/pdf/EJ_8-4.pdf","http://www.glomis.com/ej/pdf/EJ_8-4.pdf","http://blue.utb.edu/aschwarzbach/publications/MangroveAmerNaturalist.pdf","http://blue.utb.edu/aschwarzbach/publications/MangroveAmerNaturalist.pdf","http://www.ejabf.eg.net/pdf/vol-14-n-2/6.pdf","http://www.ejabf.eg.net/pdf/vol-14-n-2/6.pdf","http://www.nwrc.usgs.gov/climate/fs95_97.pdf","http://www.nwrc.usgs.gov/climate/fs95_97.pdf","http://www.wlf.state.la.us/pdfs/experience/Coastal%20Mangrove-Marsh%20Shrubland.pdf","http://www.wlf.state.la.us/pdfs/experience/Coastal%20Mangrove-Marsh%20Shrubland.pdf","http://maps.cathalac.org/Downloads/data/bz/bz_mangroves_1980-2010_highres.pdf","http://www.actfr.jcu.edu.au/idc/groups/public/documents/journal_article/jcudev_015628.pdf","http://ambergriscaye.com/pages/town/art/Pelican_Review.pdf","http://ambergriscaye.com/pages/town/art/Pelican_Review.pdf","http://www.servir.net/servir_bz_forest_cover_1980-2010.pdf","http://www.belizelaw.org/lawadmin/PDF%20files/cap213s.pdf","http://pdf.wri.org/working_papers/coastal_capital_belize_wp.pdf","http://maps.cathalac.org/Downloads/data/bz/bz_mangroves_1980-2010_highres.pdf","http://www.fish.wa.gov.au/Documents/recreational_fishing/fact_sheets/fact_sheet_